tOn Homes, Work, and Personhood: An Interview with Prabhu Mohapatra -- tOn Photography and History: An Interview with Alf Lüdtke -- tReflections III -- tWhy Homes Still Matter: Thoughts on Mamphela Ramphele’s A Bed Called Home -- tContributor Biographies -- tPicture Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHouses and homes are dynamic spaces within which people work to organize and secure their lives, livelihoods and relationships. Written by a team of renowned historians and anthropologists, and and accompanied by original photography by Maurice Weiss, To Be at Home: House,Work, and Self in the Modern World compares the ways people in different societies and historical periods strive to make and keep houses and homes under conditions of change, upheaval, displacement, impoverishment and violence. These conditions speak to the challenges of life in our modern world. The contributors of this volume position the home as a new nodal point between work, the self and the world to explore people’s creativity, agency and labour. Houses and homes prove complex and powerful concepts – if also often elusive – invoking places, persons, objects, emotions, values, attachments and fantasies. This book demonstrates how the relations between houses, work and the self have transformed dramatically and unpredictably under conditions of capitalism and modernity – and continue to change today.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArchitecture and society. 0aHomexPsychological aspects. 0aHomexSocial aspects. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh1 aAddlakha, Renu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlgazi, Gadi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllina, Eric, econt